There is few problems with RPC Mode of zod-openapi middleware.

1. When creating a route, if no 'request' field is specified (like for a GET route), the route is wrongly typed when using typeof router and it screw up auto completion and return types for all of the client.

2. Even if we set responses in the route, the types of the responses will be retrieved, but not the status code so it can't be used.

![image](https://github.com/honojs/middleware/assets/71818947/204501b6-6713-4254-9c9e-ebf3e7c2ab5f)

Example code:
```ts
import { createRoute, OpenAPIHono, z } from "@hono/zod-openapi";
import { hc } from "hono/client";

const router = new OpenAPIHono()
    .openapi(createRoute({
        method: 'get',
        path: '/incorrect',
        request: { // Comment this field and every types will be screwd up
            params: z.object({
                param: z.string()
            })
        },
        responses: {
            200: {
                description: 'Test',
                content: {
                    'application/json': {
                        schema: z.object({
                            ok: z.boolean()
                        })
                    }
                }
            }, 400: {
                description: 'error',
                content: {
                    'application/json': {
                        schema: z.object({
                            msg: z.string()
                        })
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }), async c => {
        if (c.req.param('param') === 'test')
            return (c.json({ ok: true }, 200));
        else
            return c.json({ msg: 'Error!' }, 400);
    })
    .get('/correct', async c => {
        if (c.req.param('param') === 'test')
            return (c.json({ ok: true }, 200));
        else
            return c.json({ msg: 'Error!' }, 400);
    });

type routerType = typeof router;

const client = hc<routerType>("http://localhost:3000");

client.correct.$get({ param: { param: "test" }}); // Works good

client.incorrect.$get({ param: { param: "test" }}); // Look at return types, and then try to comment the request field in the route

```
